Characters.

A character is the player's persona. It bundles a sound folder, a starting stat block, and a default loadout into a named identity that the game loads when the player picks that character.

The character's stats live in four plain text files alongside the sound folder — attacks.sif and bodyparts.sif for the bone-break flavor text, main.sif for the core stat block, and kombat.sif for the per-type ammo reserves and damage upgrades — so authoring a new character is mostly a matter of dropping audio in the right folder and writing a few small text files beside it.

Sound assets and main.sif files.

Character data lives in main.sif files under sounds/main/. The full path is sounds/main/characters/<character>/data/main.sif.

The paths shown below describe the decompiled loose folder form of these files. The game also accepts the compiled pack form of the same content the global main.spack at sounds/compiled/main.spack, and the lookup order is folders first, packs as fallback, so the two forms can coexist on disk. See the packs help topic for the full explanation of how decompiled folders and compiled packs interact.

Each character has its own main.sif. The file is self contained: every stat the character uses is written explicitly, and anything left out falls through to a sensible default. Most stats default to zero or one, the starting weapon defaults to a fist, and the starting shield defaults to none, so a freshly authored character only needs to write the lines it actually wants to override.

None of the data files list any sounds. The engine learns what audio a character has by scanning the character's general/ subfolder for in-game clips hurt, swing, jump, land, fall, heal, kill, life, lev, tel, turn, buy, break, death, inv, and so on and the map/ subfolder for map-event clips camera nudges, build feedback, map-update beeps, and the like. Drop a clip in the matching subfolder and the character plays it; remove it and the character goes silent for that event. There is nothing to wire up by hand because the folder layout is the audio configuration.

attacks.sif.

attacks.sif sits at sounds/main/characters/<character>/data/attacks.sif and holds a flat list of past-tense damage verbs, one per line. Whenever the character takes a bad enough fall to break a bone, the engine picks one verb from this file at random and reads back Ouch! You just <verb> your <body part>. where the body part comes from bodyparts.sif. The default file ships with words like snapped, fractured, crushed, sprained, smashed, abliderated, destroied, and shaddered, so each break sounds different. Adding more verbs widens the pool; removing all of them and leaving the file empty silences the verb half of the speech and reads back Ouch! You just  your <body part>. instead, so keep at least one entry. Each entry must be a single token with no spaces use past-tense words ending in -ed for grammatical flow. New characters can ship their own attacks.sif to give bone breaks a flavor that matches the character's voice.

bodyparts.sif.

bodyparts.sif sits at sounds/main/characters/<character>/data/bodyparts.sif and holds a flat list of body part names the character can have broken, one per line. The engine picks from this file when narrating a fresh bone break paired with attacks.sif as described above and also when it's time to remind the character that an existing break still hurts Ouch! Your <body part> hurts!. Underscores in entries are replaced with spaces when spoken, so left_ankle reads back as left ankle — write the file with underscores so the engine can also store the entry as a key without ambiguity.
The default file ships with around forty entries covering scull, neck, jaw, chest, back, the major bones of each arm and leg, and so on. Each body part is also seeded into a per-character bone damage tracker the healing cast item draws down against, so a body part not listed here can never be broken and never be healed. New characters can ship their own bodyparts.sif to limit which bones the character has e.g. a robot character with no biological parts.

main.sif field reference.

Every field in main.sif uses the form key=value, one per line. Missing fields fall back to the defaults shown below.

weapon type string: The category of the starting weapon, which must match an existing folder under main/equipments/weapons. The four folders that ship by default are archery, artillery, explosive, and melee, but any custom category folder dropped under sounds/main/equipments/weapons/ is also a valid value here. Defaults to melee. Pair this with weapon type2 to pick a specific subtype, otherwise the default fist applies. The literal word random is also accepted and rolls a random category at character load.
weapon type2 string: The subtype of the starting weapon under the chosen category, e.g. fist, knife5, AK47, rocket_launcher. Defaults to fist. The combination of weapon type and weapon type2 must point at an existing weapon folder under main/equipments/weapons, otherwise the weapon's stats fail to load. The literal word random is also accepted and rolls a random subtype at character load.

Either field can also be left random while the other is named, which gives you two partial-pin behaviors: weapon type=melee with weapon type2=random picks any subtype under the melee category, and weapon type=random with weapon type2=long_rope scans every category to find the one that owns long_rope and pins to that pair. A typo in either field a category or subtype that no longer exists on disk silently falls back to a fully random roll so authors don't have to worry about pinning to a deleted folder.

shield type string: Which shield the character starts the map already wearing. Accepts none or omitting the field to start unshielded, the folder name of any shield under main/equipments/shields to start with that shield equipped the shield's stats load immediately, just as if you'd picked it from the shields menu, or random to roll a random shield from the pack at character load. A typo a shield folder that no longer exists silently falls back to a fully random shield. Defaults to none, matching the original behavior.

attack double: The character's flat attack bonus, added to weapon damage when computing how much damage a player swing or shot deals. Stacks with the per-type damage bonus from kombat.sif damage_<type> for the equipped weapon's ammo type, or damage_melee for melee weapons, so final damage is weapon damage + attack + per-type bonus. Defaults to 0.
defence double: The character's flat defence value, multiplied by three and subtracted from incoming damage before it hits health. Defaults to 0.

points double: The starting points balance, used in the upgrade and purchase menus. Defaults to 0.

fall modifier double: How much fall damage the character takes per tile fallen on a hard landing a fall of eight or more tiles. Each tile beyond the threshold counts for fall modifier raw damage, then defence or shield defence if a shield is drawn reduces the total before it hits health. Higher values make a more fragile character that takes more damage from the same fall, lower values make a hardier one. Defaults to 21.

health double: The character's starting and maximum health pool. The character starts at full health. Drawing a weapon with a non-zero health drain value subtracts that amount from the pool on every successful fire or swing, so a high-drain weapon is paid for out of the same bar that takes damage from enemies — and if a drain takes you to zero, you die the same way any other zero-health hit kills you losing a life card, or expiring entirely if it was your last.
stamina double: The character's starting and maximum stamina pool. The character starts at full stamina, and stamina passively regenerates back up to this cap over time whenever it's below max. Each fire or melee swing of a drawn weapon subtracts the weapon's stamina drain value from the pool, so a high-drain weapon costs more to use heavily and rests up between bursts while a zero-drain weapon never touches the bar.

kills double: How many kills the character starts with on the running counter. Almost always 0 for a new character, but useful for save imports. Defaults to 0.
lives double: How many lives the character starts with. Each life refills health on death until the last one runs out. Drawing a weapon with a non-zero life drain value also spends cards out of this pool on every successful fire or swing — each drained card plays the character's life clip and refills health, exactly like a /suicide consumption, but on the very last card the drain triggers the real game-over instead of respawning. Defaults to 1.

level double: The character's starting level. Most stats and unlock checks read against this. Defaults to 1.
level modifier double: A multiplier applied to xp required for the next level. Higher numbers make leveling slower. Defaults to 1.

experience double: The character's starting xp toward the next level. Defaults to 0.
experience modifier double: A multiplier applied to xp gains, so a higher value makes a creature's xp drop count for more. Defaults to 1.
experience required double: The xp required to reach the next level on the first level up. Recomputed automatically each level after that, so this only sets the very first threshold. Defaults to 1.

kombat.sif field reference.

kombat.sif sits alongside main.sif at sounds/main/characters/<character>/data/kombat.sif and stores the character's per-type ammo reserves and damage upgrades. Every field is key=value, one per line, all defaulting to 0 when missing. The shop's ammo and damage tabs read from these and write back to them as the player buys upgrades.

damage_<type> double: The per-type damage bonus added on top of the player's attack and the weapon's own damage. There are sixteen of these, one per non-melee ammo type: damage_normal, damage_gas, damage_air, damage_battery, damage_powder, damage_arrow, damage_rocket, damage_water, damage_knife, damage_needle, damage_dart, damage_ball, damage_mana, damage_fuel, damage_rock, damage_grenade. Bought through the shop's damage tab, gated on having ever bought ammo of that type. Defaults to 0.

damage_melee double: The per-type damage bonus added when swinging a melee weapon. Always available in the shop's damage tab regardless of ammo purchases since melee doesn't consume ammo. Defaults to 0.

reserve_<type> double: The character-wide ammo pool for each non-melee type. There are sixteen of these, one per type listed under damage_<type> above no melee since melee doesn't reload. Bought through the shop's ammo tab. Reload pulls from the matching reserve into the equipped weapon's loaded ammo, so two weapons of the same type share the same pool. Defaults to 0.

bought_<type> int: A sticky flag 1 or 0 that the parser flips to 1 the first time the player buys ammo of that type. Once set, the matching damage_<type> entry stays visible in the shop's damage tab forever — even after the reserve is spent back to zero — so the player can keep upgrading damage for that type. Created automatically on the first ammo purchase, so a fresh kombat.sif doesn't need to declare these explicitly.
